question.text: A researcher measures the density of magnesium (7.34 g•mL –1 ) in four separate trials. Which of the following statements best describes her measurements? Density, g • mL –1 7.45 8.20 6.36 8.90

explanation.concept_text: To solve this problem involving accuracy vs. precision , let’s first define the two properties: Accuracy describes the overall closeness of experimental values to the true literature value. If a set of data is accurate, that means the experimental values are grouped around the true value. Precision describes the overall consistency of experimental values. If a set of data is precise, that means the experimental values are grouped closely to each other, but not necessarily around the true value. Accuracy and precision are independent of one another. Density, g • mL –1 7.45 8.20 6.36 8.90 In this case, we are told that the true density of magnesium is 7.34 g • mL –1 . We can see that the data presented in the table are not close to the true value, so they have low accuracy . In addition, the data points are not consistently close to each other, so they have low precision . Therefore, the answer is A .

question.text: Which of the following best represents a sample with high precision?

options.label: A.
options.text: Correctly calculating the mass of aluminum to be 75 grams.

options.label: B.
options.text: Accidentally using sugar instead of salt for an experiment.

options.label: C.
options.text: Readings for a classroom thermometer showing 70 o F each day for the past month.

options.label: D.
options.text: Reading the lowest point of the meniscus in a graduated cylinder with water.

options.label: E.
options.text: Taring the weigh scale for only half of the experiment’s measurements.

correct_answer_text: Readings for a classroom thermometer showing 70 o F each day for the past month.

explanation.concept_text: To solve this problem involving accuracy vs. precision , let’s first define the two properties: Accuracy describes the overall closeness of experimental values to the true literature value. If a set of data is accurate, that means the experimental values are grouped around the true value. Precision describes the overall consistency of experimental values. If a set of data is precise, that means the experimental values are grouped closely to each other, but not necessarily around the true value. Accuracy and precision are independent of one another. Option A. Correctly calculating the mass of aluminum to be 75 grams. Incorrect. Although this implies that the calculated mass is close to the true value, this indicates high accuracy , not high precision. To determine precision, we require multiple data points. Option B. Accidentally using sugar instead of salt for an experiment. Incorrect. Because the intention was to use salt, not sugar, this indicates a mistake, and has no implications on precision. Option C. Readings for a classroom thermometer showing 70 o F each day for the past month. Correct. Although we do not know the classroom’s true temperature, a consistent reading of 70 o F each day for an entire month indicates high precision . Option D. Reading the lowest point of the meniscus in a graduated cylinder with water. Incorrect. Although it is good practice to read the lowest point of the meniscus in a graduated cylinder with water, this indicates high accuracy , not high precision. To determine precision, we require multiple data points. Option E. Taring the weigh scale for only half of the experiment’s measurements. Incorrect. Since half of the measurements did not involve taring, this indicates that measurements will have low accuracy and low precision . Therefore, the answer is C .
